WEBVTT

00:08.400 --> 00:12.340
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

00:27.980 --> 00:33.280
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

00:36.080 --> 00:37.600
And here are your hosts.

00:41.960 --> 00:44.080
This is David Carson and Errol Lane.

00:44.500 --> 00:48.400
British-born author James P. Hogan has gained a reputation as one of the premier writers

00:48.400 --> 00:50.000
of hard science fiction working today.

00:50.540 --> 00:54.880
He's published seven novels so far, including In Here at the Stars, The Gentle Giants of

00:54.880 --> 00:59.940
Gain-A-Meade, Giant Star, Thrice Upon a Time, The Two Faces of Tomorrow, and his latest

00:59.940 --> 01:01.100
Voyage from yesteryear.

01:01.100 --> 01:03.040
Hogan tells us how he became an author.

01:48.960 --> 01:50.360
For

01:58.260 --> 02:03.140
20 years, Hogan worked as a systems designer for computers, then sold computers to scientists

02:03.140 --> 02:04.460
for use in their research.

02:04.920 --> 02:08.960
Associating with scientists as he did, Hogan was exposed to all sorts of current scientific

02:08.960 --> 02:13.260
research, and he would make use of his scientific context when he began to write seriously.

02:43.260 --> 02:45.340
The chances were 10 to 1.

02:45.520 --> 02:50.120
I had a customer specializing in that field, and I just had to, if I needed some background

02:50.500 --> 02:55.040
information on a particular topic, I could almost guarantee I had a phone number in my

02:55.040 --> 02:57.260
diary as a guy who could talk all day about it.

02:58.440 --> 03:00.200
And they loved doing it, as well.

03:00.360 --> 03:03.700
I used to call them, and they'd say, I'd like to come and talk to you tomorrow.

03:04.800 --> 03:07.380
Well, we're a little busy, but what's it about?

03:07.620 --> 03:10.400
Oh, I need some help with the book I'm working on.

03:10.520 --> 03:11.460
Well, why didn't you say so?

03:11.600 --> 03:12.540
What times do you want to show up?

03:12.540 --> 03:13.960
I may talk all day.

03:15.020 --> 03:26.160
I think this is one of the interesting sites of selling computers into this kind of area.

03:26.380 --> 03:33.340
You can imagine some of these specialists, they talk to bacteria all day long or whatever,

03:33.620 --> 03:36.420
and they end up shutting the back rooms of universities.

03:37.300 --> 03:41.440
And maybe there are four people on the planet they can talk to who understand their language.

03:41.440 --> 03:50.260
And sometimes they find it hard to believe that somebody from the world outside that

03:50.260 --> 03:55.920
has walked in off the street is sincerely interested to sit down and talk to them.

03:56.120 --> 04:00.300
And he's curious, and he wants to know what they're doing, wants to have it explained.

04:01.540 --> 04:06.200
So, writing about his experiences with scientists, Hogan found that he was a science fiction writer.

04:07.720 --> 04:11.820
I didn't particularly set out to be a science fiction writer.

04:12.060 --> 04:13.440
I suppose I became one by accident.

04:14.260 --> 04:19.000
I just always wanted to write and started writing stories about the little bit of life

04:19.000 --> 04:24.560
that I'd had some personal experience of, and was told I was a science fiction writer,

04:24.700 --> 04:25.460
and I said, how's that?

04:25.780 --> 04:29.720
And they said, well, the publisher is publishing it under their science fiction imprint,

04:29.900 --> 04:30.860
so we guess you have to be.

04:30.980 --> 04:31.620
So I said, OK.

04:32.740 --> 04:34.480
And it kind of started out like that.

04:35.620 --> 04:38.520
Hogan's books are scientifically accurate and highly realistic.

04:38.980 --> 04:41.680
He's been called the man who put science back into science fiction.

04:42.060 --> 04:44.620
Next time we'll talk to James P. Hogan about some of his novels.

04:52.020 --> 04:56.700
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin Science Fiction

04:56.700 --> 05:00.520
Association produced in conjunction with Odessa College in Odessa, Texas.

