Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

06:00.980 --> 06:06.260
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

06:09.290 --> 06:10.560
And here are your hosts.

06:14.820 --> 06:16.000
This is Daryl Lane.

06:16.220 --> 06:16.840
And David Carson.

06:17.220 --> 06:22.120
James P. Hogan's 1977 science fiction novel, Inherit the Stars, should be required reading

06:22.120 --> 06:25.160
for anyone who demands scientific accuracy in an exciting narrative.

06:25.600 --> 06:27.500
The book takes place some 50 years in the future.

06:28.000 --> 06:30.160
A skeleton inside a space suit is found on the moon.

06:30.560 --> 06:33.240
That's interesting enough, but what follows is even more provocative.

06:33.880 --> 06:37.280
The skeleton is a human one, and it's been on the moon for 50,000 years.

06:37.620 --> 06:40.900
The scientific unraveling of this mystery forms the basis of the novel.

06:41.420 --> 06:44.800
It's like a detective story, and Hogan talks about the origins of the idea.

06:46.520 --> 06:51.680
2001 was one of the factors that inspired me to write Inherit the Stars.

06:52.060 --> 06:58.740
I loved the idea of something being found, a mystery, being uncovered in the course of

06:58.740 --> 07:05.680
lunar exploration that was sufficiently intriguing to motivate a lot of scientists into unraveling

07:05.680 --> 07:05.800
it.

07:06.600 --> 07:14.620
It seemed a good opportunity to set the scientific detective story that I wanted to write.

07:15.320 --> 07:19.400
You know, okay, let's have the detective story, or the mystery that the detectives are trying

07:19.400 --> 07:23.300
to solve hinge around something that's turned up on the moon.

07:24.020 --> 07:27.880
Well, dead bodies are always pretty good for detective stories.

07:30.180 --> 07:35.200
It ought to be a more interesting dead body than the standard detective thriller.

07:35.200 --> 07:40.860
So let's make it 50,000 years old in human, which raises the whole, opens up the whole

07:40.860 --> 07:43.720
bag of words, and let's just see how they unravel that.

07:44.180 --> 07:54.540
I wanted the ending to be a bit of a twist, a bit unexpected, a bit of a surprise, but

07:54.540 --> 07:57.880
nevertheless plausible and rational within the context of the story.

07:57.880 --> 08:07.240
I didn't want to bring in mystical agencies or strange laws of physics or anything like

08:07.240 --> 08:08.660
this to hold it together.

08:09.540 --> 08:14.400
The entire scientific community of Earth starts to work on the baffling problem of the space-suited

08:14.400 --> 08:17.120
50,000-year-old human skeleton, which they name Charlie.

08:17.700 --> 08:22.820
They soon find remnants on the moon of Charlie's culture, a map of an unfamiliar planet, scraps

08:22.820 --> 08:26.720
of Charlie's diary in an unfamiliar language, and some technological artifacts.

08:26.720 --> 08:31.460
With such clues, the scientists begin to piece together the incredible story of who Charlie

08:31.460 --> 08:32.780
was and why he was human.

08:33.500 --> 08:36.220
Hogan says the book sort of defines what science is all about.

08:36.720 --> 08:40.120
It counters some of the distorted images of scientists Hogan has seen in fiction.

08:41.460 --> 08:46.240
Scientists were always eccentric and they wore odd colored shoes and they drew cabbages

08:46.240 --> 08:49.360
that ate people and they wanted to conquer the world or something.

08:49.360 --> 08:58.260
And there are these cute public impressions of scientists as people who run down the street

08:58.260 --> 09:00.500
with no clothes on shouting Eureka.

09:06.740 --> 09:16.580
Or you read phrases like it came to him in a flash and you read on and what came to him

09:16.580 --> 09:20.200
in a flash would have been enough to keep Einstein busy for the next 20 years.

09:21.440 --> 09:28.760
And real science, you know, there are insights, there are strokes of genius, but the overwhelming

09:29.860 --> 09:35.660
bulk of the work is done by a lot of unsung heroes, a lot of people doing nothing really

09:35.660 --> 09:42.160
dramatic or exciting but just meticulously sifting through details, collecting information.

09:43.360 --> 09:47.020
For generations and for centuries, all different parts of the world.

09:47.720 --> 09:53.640
And it's really like putting together a huge jigsaw puzzle, lots of people cutting out pieces

09:53.640 --> 09:58.460
and pushing them around and every now and again somebody will take a huge chunk in this corner

09:58.460 --> 10:01.780
and see that it fits with a huge chunk down there and that's a breakthrough.

10:02.380 --> 10:03.280
And so it goes on.

10:03.860 --> 10:06.520
And it really is a detective story.

10:06.860 --> 10:09.440
I think it's a far more exciting one than most detective fiction.

10:09.980 --> 10:14.920
We strongly recommend you read Inherit the Stars to find out the solution to the mystery surrounding Charlie.

10:15.340 --> 10:21.420
Hogan wrote two sequels to Inherit the Stars and all three form a trilogy that presents an awesome view of man's origins.

10:21.980 --> 10:24.320
Next time we'll talk with Hogan about those other two books.

10:31.440 --> 10:36.740
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin Science Fiction Association

10:36.740 --> 10:39.900
produced in conjunction with Odessa College in Odessa, Texas.

